Sub-Sahara Africa Stocks: Eveready, National Bank of Kenya Fall

-- B y   C h r i s   K a y
-- 
2011-05-24T16:09:44Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-24/sub-sahara-africa-stocks-report-eveready-national-bank-of-kenya-retreat.html
Namibia’s FTSE/ Namibia Overall Index (FTN098) 
jumped for the first day in three, advancing 1.5 percent to
840.76 by the 4 p.m. end of trading in  Windhoek .  Mauritius’s SEMDEX Index fell for a second day, retreating
less than 0.1 percent to 2,084.37 by the 1:30 p.m. close in Port
Louis, the lowest since May 9.  Kenya ’s All-Share Index fell for
a third day, declining less than 0.1 percent to 74.88 by the 3
p.m. close in Nairobi. The Nigerian Stock Exchange All-Share
Index retreated for the second day, less than 0.1 percent to
25,738.80 by the 2:30 p.m. close in Lagos, according to a
statement on the exchange’s website. The Ghana Stock Exchange
Composite Index snapped two days of gains, erasing less than 0.1
percent to 1,178.94 by the 3 p.m. close in Accra.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan  Africa ,
excluding  South Africa . Stock symbols are in parentheses.  Eveready East Africa Ltd. (EVRD)  , the biggest dry-cell
battery maker in the region, slumped 15 cents, or 6.5 percent,
to 2.15 shillings, the biggest drop since Dec. 30, after
Business Daily reported that the Nairobi-based manufacturer
plans to close its Kenyan plant, citing Managing Director
Jackson Mutua.  National Bank of Kenya Ltd. (NBKL)  , a state-owned
lender, retreated 50 cents, or 1.4 percent, to 35 shillings, the
lowest level since March 2010, after it said net income in the
first quarter fell 30 percent to 231.5 million shillings ($2.7
million).  To contact the reporter on this story:
